c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aFor two centuries, Gesamtkunstwerk—the ideal of the “total work of art”—has exerted a powerful influence over artistic discourse and practice, spurring new forms of collaboration and provoking debates over the political instrumentalization of art. Despite its popular conflation with the work of Richard Wagner, Gesamtkunstwerk’s lineage and legacies extend well beyond German Romanticism, as this wide-ranging collection demonstrates. In eleven compact chapters, scholars from a variety of disciplines trace the idea’s evolution in German-speaking Europe, from its foundations in the early nineteenth century to its manifold articulations and reimaginings in the twentieth century and beyond, providing an uncommonly broad perspective on a distinctly modern cultural form.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 07. Nov 2022) 0aArts, GermanxPhilosophy. 0aSenses and sensation in art. 7aART / History / Modern (late 19th Century to 1945).2bisacsh1 aAmidon, Kevin S., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aAnger, Jenny, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aApplegate, Celia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCalico, Joy H., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGoodwin, Julia, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aHeisler Jr., Wayne, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImhoof, David, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aImhoof, David, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aMenninger, Margaret Eleanor, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMenninger, Margaret Eleanor, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aPederson